“So Chidi showed up at Marisol’s place with a chart on his phone,” Hana said. “Told her he’d tripled a five-grand position in six weeks using options on this small biotech stock. Said she was leaving money on the table letting her down payment sit in a money market fund.”

“Was the trade profitable for him?” I asked.

“Possibly. Doesn’t matter. What matters is that her financial position is nothing like his. She’s house hunting, needs the full amount in fifteen months, no margin for error. He’s renting, single, mid-career—can absorb a 70 percent drawdown.”

“Did she act on the advice?”

“She put twenty percent of the savings into a short-term call spread. Same stock. Two weeks later, the company missed trial enrollment targets. The position lost 85 percent. She didn’t rebalance. Didn’t sell. Just left it.”

“How’d it get corrected?”

“Marisol’s brother works in retirement plan administration. Saw a line item on her brokerage statement. Called her. Asked why she had a leveraged options position in a speculative stock. She said Chidi said it was safe because he’d made money. Her brother asked how much of the down payment it was. When she told him, he told her to close it.”

“Did she?”

“Partially. She exited the calls, took the loss. Still has a small position in the underlying stock. Says she’s ‘averaging down.’ ”

“Is Chidi advising others?”

“No sign. But the mechanism’s common: recent personal success gets mistaken for replicable strategy. High volatility assets, short-term wins—people conflate outcome with method. The liquidity need, the time horizon, the loss tolerance—none of that showed up in the logic.”

“What’s she doing now with the rest of the fund?”

Rebalancing into a short-duration bond ladder. Set monthly contributions to rebuild the withdrawn amount. Adjusted target home price downward.

