In early 2022, as markets neared a short-term peak, Dmitri suggested Ingrid consider reallocating the $42,000 she’d saved for a house down payment into leveraged options on a small biotech stock. He framed it as a "short-term bridge" — the idea being that a quick run-up could fund both a larger down payment and closing costs, possibly on a property in a more desirable area. At the time, the broader index had risen for eight straight months, and similar speculative positions had produced visible gains for some peers in their social circle.

Ingrid had saved the money over three years, keeping it in a high-yield savings account with scheduled auto-transfers. The plan had been to close on a property within the next nine to fifteen months. Dmitri’s calculation hinged on a six-week window: buy call options with 70% of the funds, keep the rest liquid, and exit before expiration if targets were met.

“We’re not talking about holding,” Dmitri said. “Just let it ride through the data readout. If it lands, you pull triple. If not, you still have enough for a starter home—just maybe one repair behind.”

The options were tied to a company awaiting regulatory approval. Approval was uncertain, and the options themselves were two strikes out of the money with expiration in 48 days. The total premium paid would have represented more than three times the average monthly mortgage she’d projected.

She didn’t follow through, but rewrote her budget that week to allow for house-hunting in a lower price band.

