Ingrid had read the book twice by the time she transferred $68,000 from her house-down-payment account into her brokerage. The book argued that measurable risk wasn’t the same as unacceptable risk, and that diversification across asset classes could substitute for traditional liquidity buffers. She kept a notebook of spreadsheets tracking implied volatility, entry points on a small biotech stock she’d identified, and hypothetical returns if she leveraged options with consistent 30-delta hedges. Her numbers assumed a 60% win rate on short puts and a maximum drawdown of 22%. The house wasn’t set to close for another five months, the rates in her savings account were negligible, and the book repeatedly cited instances where delayed homeownership had been offset by controlled, tactical option-writing strategies under defined conditions: market volatility above 18, low margin requirements, high rolling frequency.

Kofi, who had mentioned the book at a work dinner, had used a similar strategy the year before—rolled short puts on a mid-cap stock while saving for a condo. He’d timed exits around earnings with a trailing stop, avoided assignment, and bought his unit six months later with 11% net gains on his trading account. No margin calls, no close calls. Marisol had also started paper-trading after reading it, though she hadn’t yet moved real funds. She was waiting for her rent increase to hit before reassessing risk capacity.

Ingrid structured her first three trades exactly as the book recommended: weekly puts, 0.30 delta, 30 days to expiration. The first two returned the expected premium. The third coincided with unexpected news about the biotech’s trial results. The stock gapped down 39% overnight. Her stop-loss wasn’t triggered—he hadn't seen the open—so assignment was automatic. Selling shares she didn’t own at strike price created a margin shortfall. The broker issued a collateral call she couldn’t meet without liquidating other assets.

She reset her allocation parameters the Friday after the assignment. The house search remains on hold. Kofi suggested increasing position size only after three consecutive months of positive roll yield.

