Dmitri took the call during lunch, standing outside the building. The voice on the line was upbeat, said he’d been watching Dmitri’s account grow over the past few months — small regular deposits, mostly into low-cost index funds. Then came the suggestion: open a margin capacity on the brokerage account. “You’re a disciplined saver,” the advisor said. “Now it’s time to let the portfolio work harder.” Dmitri didn’t ask how. He signed the amendment form later that day.

Two weeks later, Noor noticed the change when she glanced at Dmitri’s phone screen while they waited for coffee. “You’re using margin?” she asked. He said the advisor had called it “a low-cost way to increase exposure” and promised returns would compound faster. Dmitri had already used about a third of his available margin to buy a cryptocurrency and a small biotech stock, both volatile. “He said just start small. Like, borrow five percent of your equity. No big risk.”

The account was worth about $38,000 at the time, with $12,000 in cash deposits over the previous ten months. Margin capacity was approved for $19,000. The crypto position declined 32% within ten days. Dmitri didn’t sell. Interest on the margin balance began accruing at 7.25% annually, applied daily. The brokerage sent a margin call notice on a Tuesday morning. Dmitri transferred $3,000 from his checking account to meet the requirement. He didn’t liquidate either holding.

Felix, who worked in risk compliance at a different firm, reviewed the statements later. Pointed out that the interest rate on margin was higher than the expected dividend yield of most stable equities. Also that volatility in the biotech stock meant a 15% drop could trigger another margin call even if the crypto holding stabilized. “Borrowing magnifies both gains and losses,” he said. “But the losses come first when prices fall. The loan doesn’t wait.”

Noor suggested switching back to cash-only trading. Rebuild the buffer. “You were doing fine before the call,” she said. Dmitri paused his automatic investments while he figured out the tax implications of selling the biotech shares at a loss.

Felix drew a simple table on a napkin: one column for account value, one for margin balance, one labeled “equity.” He walked through what happened if the portfolio dropped another 20% from that point. The numbers in the equity column went negative.

Dmitri asked if the broker typically warned people when the ratio got close. Felix said some did, some didn’t. It depended on the routing.

Noor said she’d read about hedge funds using leverage during the recovery cycle. Asked if the timing made a difference. Felix didn’t answer right away.

