Owen was twenty-three. He worked part-time at a bike shop, no benefits, no 401(k) match.

He had four thousand dollars in a Roth IRA. Grew it to eleven over two years. Mostly in a cryptocurrency that doubled three times in a row. People online said it was still early.

Devon told him over pizza: “If it’s going up, pull the money out. Put it all back in right after. Buy more low. You’re not cashing out—you’re rotating.”

Owen checked his account. Sixteen percent gain in a week. He took out six thousand. Left the rest to ride.

He bought a chunk of a small biotech stock. One forum called it “the next moonshot.” It dropped forty percent in three days.

He re-deposited the Roth contribution a month later. Couldn’t re-deposit the gains. Tax penalty applied anyway.

Sanjay asked if he knew about annual contribution limits. Owen said he thought he read somewhere that you could “rebalance across years.”

His cousin had done it once. Seemed fine.

Owen still gets a notice every January about excess contributions.
